92// minimum reasonable default.

146// The first field contains the value that the switch produces when a certain
147// case group is selected, and the second field is a vector containing the
148// cases composing the case group.
149using SwitchCaseResultVectorTy =
150 SmallVector<std::pair<Constant *, SmallVector<ConstantInt *, 4>>, 2>;
151
152// The first field contains the phi node that generates a result of the switch
153// and the second field contains the value generated for a certain case in the
154// switch for that PHI.
155using SwitchCaseResultsTy = SmallVector<std::pair<PHINode *, Constant *>, 4>;
156
157/// ValueEqualityComparisonCase - Represents a case of a switch.
158struct ValueEqualityComparisonCase {
159 ConstantInt *Value;
160 BasicBlock *Dest;
161
162 ValueEqualityComparisonCase(ConstantInt *Value, BasicBlock *Dest)
163 : Value(Value), Dest(Dest) {}
164
165 bool operator<(ValueEqualityComparisonCase RHS) const {
166 // Comparing pointers is ok as we only rely on the order for uniquing.
167 return Value < RHS.Value;
168 }
169
170 bool operator==(BasicBlock *RHSDest) const { return Dest == RHSDest; }
171};

221/// Return true if it is safe to merge these two
222/// terminator instructions together.
223static bool
224SafeToMergeTerminators(Instruction *SI1, Instruction *SI2,
225 SmallSetVector<BasicBlock *, 4> *FailBlocks = nullptr) {
226 if (SI1 == SI2)
227 return false; // Can't merge with self!
228
229 // It is not safe to merge these two switch instructions if they have a common
230 // successor, and if that successor has a PHI node, and if *that* PHI node has
231 // conflicting incoming values from the two switch blocks.
232 BasicBlock *SI1BB = SI1->getParent();
233 BasicBlock *SI2BB = SI2->getParent();
234
235 SmallPtrSet<BasicBlock *, 16> SI1Succs(succ_begin(SI1BB), succ_end(SI1BB));
236 bool Fail = false;
237 for (BasicBlock *Succ : successors(SI2BB))
238 if (SI1Succs.count(Succ))
239 for (BasicBlock::iterator BBI = Succ->begin(); isa<PHINode>(BBI); ++BBI) {
240 PHINode *PN = cast<PHINode>(BBI);
241 if (PN->getIncomingValueForBlock(SI1BB) !=
242 PN->getIncomingValueForBlock(SI2BB)) {
243 if (FailBlocks)
244 FailBlocks->insert(Succ);
245 Fail = true;
246 }
247 }
248
249 return !Fail;
250}
251
252/// Return true if it is safe and profitable to merge these two terminator
253/// instructions together, where SI1 is an unconditional branch. PhiNodes will
254/// store all PHI nodes in common successors.
255static bool
256isProfitableToFoldUnconditional(BranchInst *SI1, BranchInst *SI2,
257 Instruction *Cond,
258 SmallVectorImpl<PHINode *> &PhiNodes) {
259 if (SI1 == SI2)
260 return false; // Can't merge with self!
261 assert(SI1->isUnconditional() && SI2->isConditional());
262
263 // We fold the unconditional branch if we can easily update all PHI nodes in
264 // common successors:
265 // 1> We have a constant incoming value for the conditional branch;
266 // 2> We have "Cond" as the incoming value for the unconditional branch;
267 // 3> SI2->getCondition() and Cond have same operands.
268 CmpInst *Ci2 = dyn_cast<CmpInst>(SI2->getCondition());
269 if (!Ci2)
270 return false;
271 if (!(Cond->getOperand(0) == Ci2->getOperand(0) &&
272 Cond->getOperand(1) == Ci2->getOperand(1)) &&
273 !(Cond->getOperand(0) == Ci2->getOperand(1) &&
274 Cond->getOperand(1) == Ci2->getOperand(0)))
275 return false;
276
277 BasicBlock *SI1BB = SI1->getParent();
278 BasicBlock *SI2BB = SI2->getParent();
279 SmallPtrSet<BasicBlock *, 16> SI1Succs(succ_begin(SI1BB), succ_end(SI1BB));
280 for (BasicBlock *Succ : successors(SI2BB))
281 if (SI1Succs.count(Succ))
282 for (BasicBlock::iterator BBI = Succ->begin(); isa<PHINode>(BBI); ++BBI) {
283 PHINode *PN = cast<PHINode>(BBI);
284 if (PN->getIncomingValueForBlock(SI1BB) != Cond ||
285 !isa<ConstantInt>(PN->getIncomingValueForBlock(SI2BB)))
286 return false;
287 PhiNodes.push_back(PN);
288 }
289 return true;
290}
291
292/// Update PHI nodes in Succ to indicate that there will now be entries in it
293/// from the 'NewPred' block. The values that will be flowing into the PHI nodes
294/// will be the same as those coming in from ExistPred, an existing predecessor
295/// of Succ.
296static void AddPredecessorToBlock(BasicBlock *Succ, BasicBlock *NewPred,
297 BasicBlock *ExistPred,
298 MemorySSAUpdater *MSSAU = nullptr) {
299 for (PHINode &PN : Succ->phis())
300 PN.addIncoming(PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(ExistPred), NewPred);
301 if (MSSAU)
302 if (auto *MPhi = MSSAU->getMemorySSA()->getMemoryAccess(Succ))
303 MPhi->addIncoming(MPhi->getIncomingValueForBlock(ExistPred), NewPred);
304}

306/// Compute an abstract "cost" of speculating the given instruction,
307/// which is assumed to be safe to speculate. TCC_Free means cheap,
308/// TCC_Basic means less cheap, and TCC_Expensive means prohibitively
309/// expensive.
310static unsigned ComputeSpeculationCost(const User *I,
311 const TargetTransformInfo &TTI) {
312 assert(isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(I) &&
313 "Instruction is not safe to speculatively execute!");
314 return TTI.getUserCost(I);
315}
316
317/// If we have a merge point of an "if condition" as accepted above,
318/// return true if the specified value dominates the block. We
319/// don't handle the true generality of domination here, just a special case
320/// which works well enough for us.
321///
322/// If AggressiveInsts is non-null, and if V does not dominate BB, we check to
323/// see if V (which must be an instruction) and its recursive operands
324/// that do not dominate BB have a combined cost lower than CostRemaining and
325/// are non-trapping. If both are true, the instruction is inserted into the
326/// set and true is returned.
327///
328/// The cost for most non-trapping instructions is defined as 1 except for
329/// Select whose cost is 2.
330///
331/// After this function returns, CostRemaining is decreased by the cost of
332/// V plus its non-dominating operands. If that cost is greater than
333/// CostRemaining, false is returned and CostRemaining is undefined.
334static bool DominatesMergePoint(Value *V, BasicBlock *BB,
335 SmallPtrSetImpl<Instruction *> &AggressiveInsts,
336 unsigned &CostRemaining,
337 const TargetTransformInfo &TTI,
338 unsigned Depth = 0) {
339 // It is possible to hit a zero-cost cycle (phi/gep instructions for example),
340 // so limit the recursion depth.
341 // TODO: While this recursion limit does prevent pathological behavior, it
342 // would be better to track visited instructions to avoid cycles.
343 if (Depth == MaxSpeculationDepth)
344 return false;
345
346 Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V);
347 if (!I) {
348 // Non-instructions all dominate instructions, but not all constantexprs
349 // can be executed unconditionally.
350 if (ConstantExpr *C = dyn_cast<ConstantExpr>(V))
351 if (C->canTrap())
352 return false;
353 return true;
354 }
355 BasicBlock *PBB = I->getParent();
356
357 // We don't want to allow weird loops that might have the "if condition" in
358 // the bottom of this block.
359 if (PBB == BB)
360 return false;
361
362 // If this instruction is defined in a block that contains an unconditional
363 // branch to BB, then it must be in the 'conditional' part of the "if
364 // statement". If not, it definitely dominates the region.
365 BranchInst *BI = dyn_cast<BranchInst>(PBB->getTerminator());
366 if (!BI || BI->isConditional() || BI->getSuccessor(0) != BB)
367 return true;
368
369 // If we have seen this instruction before, don't count it again.
370 if (AggressiveInsts.count(I))
371 return true;
372
373 // Okay, it looks like the instruction IS in the "condition". Check to
374 // see if it's a cheap instruction to unconditionally compute, and if it
375 // only uses stuff defined outside of the condition. If so, hoist it out.
376 if (!isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(I))
377 return false;
378
379 unsigned Cost = ComputeSpeculationCost(I, TTI);
380
381 // Allow exactly one instruction to be speculated regardless of its cost
382 // (as long as it is safe to do so).
383 // This is intended to flatten the CFG even if the instruction is a division
384 // or other expensive operation. The speculation of an expensive instruction
385 // is expected to be undone in CodeGenPrepare if the speculation has not
386 // enabled further IR optimizations.
387 if (Cost > CostRemaining &&
388 (!SpeculateOneExpensiveInst || !AggressiveInsts.empty() || Depth > 0))
389 return false;
390
391 // Avoid unsigned wrap.
392 CostRemaining = (Cost > CostRemaining) ? 0 : CostRemaining - Cost;
393
394 // Okay, we can only really hoist these out if their operands do
395 // not take us over the cost threshold.
396 for (User::op_iterator i = I->op_begin(), e = I->op_end(); i != e; ++i)
397 if (!DominatesMergePoint(*i, BB, AggressiveInsts, CostRemaining, TTI,
398 Depth + 1))
399 return false;
400 // Okay, it's safe to do this! Remember this instruction.
401 AggressiveInsts.insert(I);
402 return true;
403}

405/// Extract ConstantInt from value, looking through IntToPtr
406/// and PointerNullValue. Return NULL if value is not a constant int.
407static ConstantInt *GetConstantInt(Value *V, const DataLayout &DL) {
408 // Normal constant int.
409 ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(V);
410 if (CI || !isa<Constant>(V) || !V->getType()->isPointerTy())
411 return CI;
412
413 // This is some kind of pointer constant. Turn it into a pointer-sized
414 // ConstantInt if possible.
415 IntegerType *PtrTy = cast<IntegerType>(DL.getIntPtrType(V->getType()));
416
417 // Null pointer means 0, see SelectionDAGBuilder::getValue(const Value*).
418 if (isa<ConstantPointerNull>(V))
419 return ConstantInt::get(PtrTy, 0);
420
421 // IntToPtr const int.
422 if (ConstantExpr *CE = dyn_cast<ConstantExpr>(V))
423 if (CE->getOpcode() == Instruction::IntToPtr)
424 if (ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(CE->getOperand(0))) {
425 // The constant is very likely to have the right type already.
426 if (CI->getType() == PtrTy)
427 return CI;
428 else
429 return cast<ConstantInt>(
430 ConstantExpr::getIntegerCast(CI, PtrTy, /*isSigned=*/false));
431 }
432 return nullptr;
433}

437/// Given a chain of or (||) or and (&&) comparison of a value against a
438/// constant, this will try to recover the information required for a switch
439/// structure.
440/// It will depth-first traverse the chain of comparison, seeking for patterns
441/// like %a == 12 or %a < 4 and combine them to produce a set of integer
442/// representing the different cases for the switch.
443/// Note that if the chain is composed of '||' it will build the set of elements
444/// that matches the comparisons (i.e. any of this value validate the chain)
445/// while for a chain of '&&' it will build the set elements that make the test
446/// fail.
447struct ConstantComparesGatherer {
448 const DataLayout &DL;
449
450 /// Value found for the switch comparison
451 Value *CompValue = nullptr;
452
453 /// Extra clause to be checked before the switch
454 Value *Extra = nullptr;
455
456 /// Set of integers to match in switch
457 SmallVector<ConstantInt *, 8> Vals;
458
459 /// Number of comparisons matched in the and/or chain
460 unsigned UsedICmps = 0;
461
462 /// Construct and compute the result for the comparison instruction Cond
463 ConstantComparesGatherer(Instruction *Cond, const DataLayout &DL) : DL(DL) {
464 gather(Cond);
465 }
466
467 ConstantComparesGatherer(const ConstantComparesGatherer &) = delete;
468 ConstantComparesGatherer &
469 operator=(const ConstantComparesGatherer &) = delete;
470
471private:
472 /// Try to set the current value used for the comparison, it succeeds only if
473 /// it wasn't set before or if the new value is the same as the old one
474 bool setValueOnce(Value *NewVal) {
475 if (CompValue && CompValue != NewVal)
476 return false;
477 CompValue = NewVal;
478 return (CompValue != nullptr);
479 }
480
481 /// Try to match Instruction "I" as a comparison against a constant and
482 /// populates the array Vals with the set of values that match (or do not
483 /// match depending on isEQ).
484 /// Return false on failure. On success, the Value the comparison matched
485 /// against is placed in CompValue.
486 /// If CompValue is already set, the function is expected to fail if a match
487 /// is found but the value compared to is different.
488 bool matchInstruction(Instruction *I, bool isEQ) {
489 // If this is an icmp against a constant, handle this as one of the cases.
490 ICmpInst *ICI;
491 ConstantInt *C;
492 if (!((ICI = dyn_cast<ICmpInst>(I)) &&
493 (C = GetConstantInt(I->getOperand(1), DL)))) {
494 return false;
495 }
496
497 Value *RHSVal;
498 const APInt *RHSC;
499
500 // Pattern match a special case
501 // (x & ~2^z) == y --> x == y || x == y|2^z
502 // This undoes a transformation done by instcombine to fuse 2 compares.
503 if (ICI->getPredicate() == (isEQ ? ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ : ICmpInst::ICMP_NE)) {
504 // It's a little bit hard to see why the following transformations are
505 // correct. Here is a CVC3 program to verify them for 64-bit values:
506
507 /*
508 ONE : BITVECTOR(64) = BVZEROEXTEND(0bin1, 63);
509 x : BITVECTOR(64);
510 y : BITVECTOR(64);
511 z : BITVECTOR(64);
512 mask : BITVECTOR(64) = BVSHL(ONE, z);
513 QUERY( (y & ~mask = y) =>
514 ((x & ~mask = y) <=> (x = y OR x = (y | mask)))
515 );
516 QUERY( (y | mask = y) =>
517 ((x | mask = y) <=> (x = y OR x = (y & ~mask)))
518 );
519 */
520
521 // Please note that each pattern must be a dual implication (<--> or
522 // iff). One directional implication can create spurious matches. If the
523 // implication is only one-way, an unsatisfiable condition on the left
524 // side can imply a satisfiable condition on the right side. Dual
525 // implication ensures that satisfiable conditions are transformed to
526 // other satisfiable conditions and unsatisfiable conditions are
527 // transformed to other unsatisfiable conditions.
528
529 // Here is a concrete example of a unsatisfiable condition on the left
530 // implying a satisfiable condition on the right:
531 //
532 // mask = (1 << z)
533 // (x & ~mask) == y --> (x == y || x == (y | mask))
534 //
535 // Substituting y = 3, z = 0 yields:
536 // (x & -2) == 3 --> (x == 3 || x == 2)
537
538 // Pattern match a special case:
539 /*
540 QUERY( (y & ~mask = y) =>
541 ((x & ~mask = y) <=> (x = y OR x = (y | mask)))
542 );
543 */
544 if (match(ICI->getOperand(0),
545 m_And(m_Value(RHSVal), m_APInt(RHSC)))) {
546 APInt Mask = ~*RHSC;
547 if (Mask.isPowerOf2() && (C->getValue() & ~Mask) == C->getValue()) {
548 // If we already have a value for the switch, it has to match!
549 if (!setValueOnce(RHSVal))
550 return false;
551
552 Vals.push_back(C);
553 Vals.push_back(
554 ConstantInt::get(C->getContext(),
555 C->getValue() | Mask));
556 UsedICmps++;
557 return true;
558 }
559 }
560
561 // Pattern match a special case:
562 /*
563 QUERY( (y | mask = y) =>
564 ((x | mask = y) <=> (x = y OR x = (y & ~mask)))
565 );
566 */
567 if (match(ICI->getOperand(0),
568 m_Or(m_Value(RHSVal), m_APInt(RHSC)))) {
569 APInt Mask = *RHSC;
570 if (Mask.isPowerOf2() && (C->getValue() | Mask) == C->getValue()) {
571 // If we already have a value for the switch, it has to match!
572 if (!setValueOnce(RHSVal))
573 return false;
574
575 Vals.push_back(C);
576 Vals.push_back(ConstantInt::get(C->getContext(),
577 C->getValue() & ~Mask));
578 UsedICmps++;
579 return true;
580 }
581 }
582
583 // If we already have a value for the switch, it has to match!
584 if (!setValueOnce(ICI->getOperand(0)))
585 return false;
586
587 UsedICmps++;
588 Vals.push_back(C);
589 return ICI->getOperand(0);
590 }
591
592 // If we have "x ult 3", for example, then we can add 0,1,2 to the set.
593 ConstantRange Span = ConstantRange::makeAllowedICmpRegion(
594 ICI->getPredicate(), C->getValue());
595
596 // Shift the range if the compare is fed by an add. This is the range
597 // compare idiom as emitted by instcombine.
598 Value *CandidateVal = I->getOperand(0);
599 if (match(I->getOperand(0), m_Add(m_Value(RHSVal), m_APInt(RHSC)))) {
600 Span = Span.subtract(*RHSC);
601 CandidateVal = RHSVal;
602 }
603
604 // If this is an and/!= check, then we are looking to build the set of
605 // value that *don't* pass the and chain. I.e. to turn "x ugt 2" into
606 // x != 0 && x != 1.
607 if (!isEQ)
608 Span = Span.inverse();
609
610 // If there are a ton of values, we don't want to make a ginormous switch.
611 if (Span.isSizeLargerThan(8) || Span.isEmptySet()) {
612 return false;
613 }
614
615 // If we already have a value for the switch, it has to match!
616 if (!setValueOnce(CandidateVal))
617 return false;
618
619 // Add all values from the range to the set
620 for (APInt Tmp = Span.getLower(); Tmp != Span.getUpper(); ++Tmp)
621 Vals.push_back(ConstantInt::get(I->getContext(), Tmp));
622
623 UsedICmps++;
624 return true;
625 }
626
627 /// Given a potentially 'or'd or 'and'd together collection of icmp
628 /// eq/ne/lt/gt instructions that compare a value against a constant, extract
629 /// the value being compared, and stick the list constants into the Vals
630 /// vector.
631 /// One "Extra" case is allowed to differ from the other.
632 void gather(Value *V) {
633 Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V);
634 bool isEQ = (I->getOpcode() == Instruction::Or);
635
636 // Keep a stack (SmallVector for efficiency) for depth-first traversal
637 SmallVector<Value *, 8> DFT;
638 SmallPtrSet<Value *, 8> Visited;
639
640 // Initialize
641 Visited.insert(V);
642 DFT.push_back(V);
643
644 while (!DFT.empty()) {
645 V = DFT.pop_back_val();
646
647 if (Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)) {
648 // If it is a || (or && depending on isEQ), process the operands.
649 if (I->getOpcode() == (isEQ ? Instruction::Or : Instruction::And)) {
650 if (Visited.insert(I->getOperand(1)).second)
651 DFT.push_back(I->getOperand(1));
652 if (Visited.insert(I->getOperand(0)).second)
653 DFT.push_back(I->getOperand(0));
654 continue;
655 }
656
657 // Try to match the current instruction
658 if (matchInstruction(I, isEQ))
659 // Match succeed, continue the loop
660 continue;
661 }
662
663 // One element of the sequence of || (or &&) could not be match as a
664 // comparison against the same value as the others.
665 // We allow only one "Extra" case to be checked before the switch
666 if (!Extra) {
667 Extra = V;
668 continue;
669 }
670 // Failed to parse a proper sequence, abort now
671 CompValue = nullptr;
672 break;
673 }
674 }
675};
676
677} // end anonymous namespace
678
679static void EraseTerminatorAndDCECond(Instruction *TI,
680 MemorySSAUpdater *MSSAU = nullptr) {
681 Instruction *Cond = nullptr;
682 if (SwitchInst *SI = dyn_cast<SwitchInst>(TI)) {
683 Cond = dyn_cast<Instruction>(SI->getCondition());
684 } else if (BranchInst *BI = dyn_cast<BranchInst>(TI)) {
685 if (BI->isConditional())
686 Cond = dyn_cast<Instruction>(BI->getCondition());
687 } else if (IndirectBrInst *IBI = dyn_cast<IndirectBrInst>(TI)) {
688 Cond = dyn_cast<Instruction>(IBI->getAddress());
689 }
690
691 TI->eraseFromParent();
692 if (Cond)
693 RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions(Cond, nullptr, MSSAU);
694}
695
696/// Return true if the specified terminator checks
697/// to see if a value is equal to constant integer value.
698Value *SimplifyCFGOpt::isValueEqualityComparison(Instruction *TI) {
699 Value *CV = nullptr;
700 if (SwitchInst *SI = dyn_cast<SwitchInst>(TI)) {
701 // Do not permit merging of large switch instructions into their
702 // predecessors unless there is only one predecessor.
703 if (!SI->getParent()->hasNPredecessorsOrMore(128 / SI->getNumSuccessors()))
704 CV = SI->getCondition();
705 } else if (BranchInst *BI = dyn_cast<BranchInst>(TI))
706 if (BI->isConditional() && BI->getCondition()->hasOneUse())
707 if (ICmpInst *ICI = dyn_cast<ICmpInst>(BI->getCondition())) {
708 if (ICI->isEquality() && GetConstantInt(ICI->getOperand(1), DL))
709 CV = ICI->getOperand(0);
710 }
711
712 // Unwrap any lossless ptrtoint cast.
713 if (CV) {
714 if (PtrToIntInst *PTII = dyn_cast<PtrToIntInst>(CV)) {
715 Value *Ptr = PTII->getPointerOperand();
716 if (PTII->getType() == DL.getIntPtrType(Ptr->getType()))
717 CV = Ptr;
718 }
719 }
720 return CV;
721}
722
723/// Given a value comparison instruction,
724/// decode all of the 'cases' that it represents and return the 'default' block.
725BasicBlock *SimplifyCFGOpt::GetValueEqualityComparisonCases(
726 Instruction *TI, std::vector<ValueEqualityComparisonCase> &Cases) {
727 if (SwitchInst *SI = dyn_cast<SwitchInst>(TI)) {
728 Cases.reserve(SI->getNumCases());
729 for (auto Case : SI->cases())
730 Cases.push_back(ValueEqualityComparisonCase(Case.getCaseValue(),
731 Case.getCaseSuccessor()));
732 return SI->getDefaultDest();
733 }
734
735 BranchInst *BI = cast<BranchInst>(TI);
736 ICmpInst *ICI = cast<ICmpInst>(BI->getCondition());
737 BasicBlock *Succ = BI->getSuccessor(ICI->getPredicate() == ICmpInst::ICMP_NE);
738 Cases.push_back(ValueEqualityComparisonCase(
739 GetConstantInt(ICI->getOperand(1), DL), Succ));
740 return BI->getSuccessor(ICI->getPredicate() == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ);
741}
742
743/// Given a vector of bb/value pairs, remove any entries
744/// in the list that match the specified block.
745static void
746EliminateBlockCases(BasicBlock *BB,
747 std::vector<ValueEqualityComparisonCase> &Cases) {
748 Cases.erase(std::remove(Cases.begin(), Cases.end(), BB), Cases.end());
749}
750
751/// Return true if there are any keys in C1 that exist in C2 as well.
752static bool ValuesOverlap(std::vector<ValueEqualityComparisonCase> &C1,
753 std::vector<ValueEqualityComparisonCase> &C2) {
754 std::vector<ValueEqualityComparisonCase> *V1 = &C1, *V2 = &C2;
755
756 // Make V1 be smaller than V2.
757 if (V1->size() > V2->size())
758 std::swap(V1, V2);
759
760 if (V1->empty())
761 return false;
762 if (V1->size() == 1) {
763 // Just scan V2.
764 ConstantInt *TheVal = (*V1)[0].Value;
765 for (unsigned i = 0, e = V2->size(); i != e; ++i)
766 if (TheVal == (*V2)[i].Value)
767 return true;
768 }
769
770 // Otherwise, just sort both lists and compare element by element.
771 array_pod_sort(V1->begin(), V1->end());
772 array_pod_sort(V2->begin(), V2->end());
773 unsigned i1 = 0, i2 = 0, e1 = V1->size(), e2 = V2->size();
774 while (i1 != e1 && i2 != e2) {
775 if ((*V1)[i1].Value == (*V2)[i2].Value)
776 return true;
777 if ((*V1)[i1].Value < (*V2)[i2].Value)
778 ++i1;
779 else
780 ++i2;
781 }
782 return false;
783}
784
785// Set branch weights on SwitchInst. This sets the metadata if there is at
786// least one non-zero weight.
787static void setBranchWeights(SwitchInst *SI, ArrayRef<uint32_t> Weights) {
788 // Check that there is at least one non-zero weight. Otherwise, pass
789 // nullptr to setMetadata which will erase the existing metadata.
790 MDNode *N = nullptr;
791 if (llvm::any_of(Weights, [](uint32_t W) { return W != 0; }))
792 N = MDBuilder(SI->getParent()->getContext()).createBranchWeights(Weights);
793 SI->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_prof, N);
794}
795
796// Similar to the above, but for branch and select instructions that take
797// exactly 2 weights.
798static void setBranchWeights(Instruction *I, uint32_t TrueWeight,
799 uint32_t FalseWeight) {
800 assert(isa<BranchInst>(I) || isa<SelectInst>(I));
801 // Check that there is at least one non-zero weight. Otherwise, pass
802 // nullptr to setMetadata which will erase the existing metadata.
803 MDNode *N = nullptr;
804 if (TrueWeight || FalseWeight)
805 N = MDBuilder(I->getParent()->getContext())
806 .createBranchWeights(TrueWeight, FalseWeight);
807 I->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_prof, N);
808}
809
810/// If TI is known to be a terminator instruction and its block is known to
811/// only have a single predecessor block, check to see if that predecessor is
812/// also a value comparison with the same value, and if that comparison
813/// determines the outcome of this comparison. If so, simplify TI. This does a
814/// very limited form of jump threading.
815bool SimplifyCFGOpt::SimplifyEqualityComparisonWithOnlyPredecessor(
816 Instruction *TI, BasicBlock *Pred, IRBuilder<> &Builder) {
817 Value *PredVal = isValueEqualityComparison(Pred->getTerminator());
818 if (!PredVal)
819 return false; // Not a value comparison in predecessor.
820
821 Value *ThisVal = isValueEqualityComparison(TI);
822 assert(ThisVal && "This isn't a value comparison!!");
823 if (ThisVal != PredVal)
824 return false; // Different predicates.
825
826 // TODO: Preserve branch weight metadata, similarly to how
827 // FoldValueComparisonIntoPredecessors preserves it.
828
829 // Find out information about when control will move from Pred to TI's block.
830 std::vector<ValueEqualityComparisonCase> PredCases;
831 BasicBlock *PredDef =
832 GetValueEqualityComparisonCases(Pred->getTerminator(), PredCases);
833 EliminateBlockCases(PredDef, PredCases); // Remove default from cases.
834
835 // Find information about how control leaves this block.
836 std::vector<ValueEqualityComparisonCase> ThisCases;
837 BasicBlock *ThisDef = GetValueEqualityComparisonCases(TI, ThisCases);
838 EliminateBlockCases(ThisDef, ThisCases); // Remove default from cases.
839
840 // If TI's block is the default block from Pred's comparison, potentially
841 // simplify TI based on this knowledge.
842 if (PredDef == TI->getParent()) {
843 // If we are here, we know that the value is none of those cases listed in
844 // PredCases. If there are any cases in ThisCases that are in PredCases, we
845 // can simplify TI.
846 if (!ValuesOverlap(PredCases, ThisCases))
847 return false;
848
849 if (isa<BranchInst>(TI)) {
850 // Okay, one of the successors of this condbr is dead. Convert it to a
851 // uncond br.
852 assert(ThisCases.size() == 1 && "Branch can only have one case!");
853 // Insert the new branch.
854 Instruction *NI = Builder.CreateBr(ThisDef);
855 (void)NI;
856
857 // Remove PHI node entries for the dead edge.
858 ThisCases[0].Dest->removePredecessor(TI->getParent());
859
860 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Threading pred instr: " << *Pred->getTerminator()
861 << "Through successor TI: " << *TI << "Leaving: " << *NI
862 << "\n");
863
864 EraseTerminatorAndDCECond(TI);
865 return true;
866 }
867
868 SwitchInst *SI = cast<SwitchInst>(TI);
869 // Okay, TI has cases that are statically dead, prune them away.
870 SmallPtrSet<Constant *, 16> DeadCases;
871 for (unsigned i = 0, e = PredCases.size(); i != e; ++i)
872 DeadCases.insert(PredCases[i].Value);
873
874 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Threading pred instr: " << *Pred->getTerminator()
875 << "Through successor TI: " << *TI);
876
877 // Collect branch weights into a vector.
878 SmallVector<uint32_t, 8> Weights;
879 MDNode *MD = SI->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_prof);
880 bool HasWeight = MD && (MD->getNumOperands() == 2 + SI->getNumCases());
881 if (HasWeight)
882 for (unsigned MD_i = 1, MD_e = MD->getNumOperands(); MD_i < MD_e;
883 ++MD_i) {
884 ConstantInt *CI = mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(MD->getOperand(MD_i));
885 Weights.push_back(CI->getValue().getZExtValue());
886 }
887 for (SwitchInst::CaseIt i = SI->case_end(), e = SI->case_begin(); i != e;) {
888 --i;
889 if (DeadCases.count(i->getCaseValue())) {
890 if (HasWeight) {
891 std::swap(Weights[i->getCaseIndex() + 1], Weights.back());
892 Weights.pop_back();
893 }
894 i->getCaseSuccessor()->removePredecessor(TI->getParent());
895 SI->removeCase(i);
896 }
897 }
898 if (HasWeight && Weights.size() >= 2)
899 setBranchWeights(SI, Weights);
900
901 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Leaving: " << *TI << "\n");
902 return true;
903 }
904
905 // Otherwise, TI's block must correspond to some matched value. Find out
906 // which value (or set of values) this is.
907 ConstantInt *TIV = nullptr;
908 BasicBlock *TIBB = TI->getParent();
909 for (unsigned i = 0, e = PredCases.size(); i != e; ++i)
910 if (PredCases[i].Dest == TIBB) {
911 if (TIV)
912 return false; // Cannot handle multiple values coming to this block.
913 TIV = PredCases[i].Value;
914 }
915 assert(TIV && "No edge from pred to succ?");
916
917 // Okay, we found the one constant that our value can be if we get into TI's
918 // BB. Find out which successor will unconditionally be branched to.
919 BasicBlock *TheRealDest = nullptr;
920 for (unsigned i = 0, e = ThisCases.size(); i != e; ++i)
921 if (ThisCases[i].Value == TIV) {
922 TheRealDest = ThisCases[i].Dest;
923 break;
924 }
925
926 // If not handled by any explicit cases, it is handled by the default case.
927 if (!TheRealDest)
928 TheRealDest = ThisDef;
929
930 // Remove PHI node entries for dead edges.
931 BasicBlock *CheckEdge = TheRealDest;
932 for (BasicBlock *Succ : successors(TIBB))
933 if (Succ != CheckEdge)
934 Succ->removePredecessor(TIBB);
935 else
936 CheckEdge = nullptr;
937
938 // Insert the new branch.
939 Instruction *NI = Builder.CreateBr(TheRealDest);
940 (void)NI;
941
942 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Threading pred instr: " << *Pred->getTerminator()
943 << "Through successor TI: " << *TI << "Leaving: " << *NI
944 << "\n");
945
946 EraseTerminatorAndDCECond(TI);
947 return true;
948}

950namespace {
951
952/// This class implements a stable ordering of constant
953/// integers that does not depend on their address. This is important for
954/// applications that sort ConstantInt's to ensure uniqueness.
955struct ConstantIntOrdering {
956 bool operator()(const ConstantInt *LHS, const ConstantInt *RHS) const {
957 return LHS->getValue().ult(RHS->getValue());
958 }
959};
960
961} // end anonymous namespace
962
963static int ConstantIntSortPredicate(ConstantInt *const *P1,
964 ConstantInt *const *P2) {
965 const ConstantInt *LHS = *P1;
966 const ConstantInt *RHS = *P2;
967 if (LHS == RHS)
968 return 0;
969 return LHS->getValue().ult(RHS->getValue()) ? 1 : -1;
970}
971
972static inline bool HasBranchWeights(const Instruction *I) {
973 MDNode *ProfMD = I->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_prof);
974 if (ProfMD && ProfMD->getOperand(0))
975 if (MDString *MDS = dyn_cast<MDString>(ProfMD->getOperand(0)))
976 return MDS->getString().equals("branch_weights");
977
978 return false;
979}
980
981/// Get Weights of a given terminator, the default weight is at the front
982/// of the vector. If TI is a conditional eq, we need to swap the branch-weight
983/// metadata.
984static void GetBranchWeights(Instruction *TI,
985 SmallVectorImpl<uint64_t> &Weights) {
986 MDNode *MD = TI->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_prof);
987 assert(MD);
988 for (unsigned i = 1, e = MD->getNumOperands(); i < e; ++i) {
989 ConstantInt *CI = mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(MD->getOperand(i));
990 Weights.push_back(CI->getValue().getZExtValue());
991 }
992
993 // If TI is a conditional eq, the default case is the false case,
994 // and the corresponding branch-weight data is at index 2. We swap the
995 // default weight to be the first entry.
996 if (BranchInst *BI = dyn_cast<BranchInst>(TI)) {
997 assert(Weights.size() == 2);
998 ICmpInst *ICI = cast<ICmpInst>(BI->getCondition());
999 if (ICI->getPredicate() == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ)
1000 std::swap(Weights.front(), Weights.back());
1001 }
1002}
1003
1004/// Keep halving the weights until all can fit in uint32_t.
1005static void FitWeights(MutableArrayRef<uint64_t> Weights) {
1006 uint64_t Max = *std::max_element(Weights.begin(), Weights.end());
1007 if (Max > UINT_MAX) {
1008 unsigned Offset = 32 - countLeadingZeros(Max);
1009 for (uint64_t &I : Weights)
1010 I >>= Offset;
1011 }
1012}
1013
1014/// The specified terminator is a value equality comparison instruction
1015/// (either a switch or a branch on "X == c").
1016/// See if any of the predecessors of the terminator block are value comparisons
1017/// on the same value. If so, and if safe to do so, fold them together.
1018bool SimplifyCFGOpt::FoldValueComparisonIntoPredecessors(Instruction *TI,
1019 IRBuilder<> &Builder) {
1020 BasicBlock *BB = TI->getParent();
1021 Value *CV = isValueEqualityComparison(TI); // CondVal
1022 assert(CV && "Not a comparison?");
1023
1024 // Don't fold if the value is a CHERI capability
1025 if (PointerType* PT = dyn_cast<PointerType>(CV->getType())) {
1026 if (isCheriPointer(PT, getDataLayoutOrNull(BB)))
1027 return false;
1028 }
1029
1030 bool Changed = false;
1031
1032 SmallVector<BasicBlock *, 16> Preds(pred_begin(BB), pred_end(BB));
1033 while (!Preds.empty()) {
1034 BasicBlock *Pred = Preds.pop_back_val();
1035
1036 // See if the predecessor is a comparison with the same value.
1037 Instruction *PTI = Pred->getTerminator();
1038 Value *PCV = isValueEqualityComparison(PTI); // PredCondVal
1039
1040 if (PCV == CV && TI != PTI) {
1041 SmallSetVector<BasicBlock*, 4> FailBlocks;
1042 if (!SafeToMergeTerminators(TI, PTI, &FailBlocks)) {
1043 for (auto *Succ : FailBlocks) {
1044 if (!SplitBlockPredecessors(Succ, TI->getParent(), ".fold.split"))
1045 return false;
1046 }
1047 }
1048
1049 // Figure out which 'cases' to copy from SI to PSI.
1050 std::vector<ValueEqualityComparisonCase> BBCases;
1051 BasicBlock *BBDefault = GetValueEqualityComparisonCases(TI, BBCases);
1052
1053 std::vector<ValueEqualityComparisonCase> PredCases;
1054 BasicBlock *PredDefault = GetValueEqualityComparisonCases(PTI, PredCases);
1055
1056 // Based on whether the default edge from PTI goes to BB or not, fill in
1057 // PredCases and PredDefault with the new switch cases we would like to
1058 // build.
1059 SmallVector<BasicBlock *, 8> NewSuccessors;
1060
1061 // Update the branch weight metadata along the way
1062 SmallVector<uint64_t, 8> Weights;
1063 bool PredHasWeights = HasBranchWeights(PTI);
1064 bool SuccHasWeights = HasBranchWeights(TI);
1065
1066 if (PredHasWeights) {
1067 GetBranchWeights(PTI, Weights);
1068 // branch-weight metadata is inconsistent here.
1069 if (Weights.size() != 1 + PredCases.size())
1070 PredHasWeights = SuccHasWeights = false;
1071 } else if (SuccHasWeights)
1072 // If there are no predecessor weights but there are successor weights,
1073 // populate Weights with 1, which will later be scaled to the sum of
1074 // successor's weights
1075 Weights.assign(1 + PredCases.size(), 1);
1076
1077 SmallVector<uint64_t, 8> SuccWeights;
1078 if (SuccHasWeights) {
1079 GetBranchWeights(TI, SuccWeights);
1080 // branch-weight metadata is inconsistent here.
1081 if (SuccWeights.size() != 1 + BBCases.size())
1082 PredHasWeights = SuccHasWeights = false;
1083 } else if (PredHasWeights)
1084 SuccWeights.assign(1 + BBCases.size(), 1);
1085
1086 if (PredDefault == BB) {
1087 // If this is the default destination from PTI, only the edges in TI
1088 // that don't occur in PTI, or that branch to BB will be activated.
1089 std::set<ConstantInt *, ConstantIntOrdering> PTIHandled;
1090 for (unsigned i = 0, e = PredCases.size(); i != e; ++i)
1091 if (PredCases[i].Dest != BB)
1092 PTIHandled.insert(PredCases[i].Value);
1093 else {
1094 // The default destination is BB, we don't need explicit targets.
1095 std::swap(PredCases[i], PredCases.back());
1096
1097 if (PredHasWeights || SuccHasWeights) {
1098 // Increase weight for the default case.
1099 Weights[0] += Weights[i + 1];
1100 std::swap(Weights[i + 1], Weights.back());
1101 Weights.pop_back();
1102 }
1103
1104 PredCases.pop_back();
1105 --i;
1106 --e;
1107 }
1108
1109 // Reconstruct the new switch statement we will be building.
1110 if (PredDefault != BBDefault) {
1111 PredDefault->removePredecessor(Pred);
1112 PredDefault = BBDefault;
1113 NewSuccessors.push_back(BBDefault);
1114 }
1115
1116 unsigned CasesFromPred = Weights.size();
1117 uint64_t ValidTotalSuccWeight = 0;
1118 for (unsigned i = 0, e = BBCases.size(); i != e; ++i)
1119 if (!PTIHandled.count(BBCases[i].Value) &&
1120 BBCases[i].Dest != BBDefault) {
1121 PredCases.push_back(BBCases[i]);
1122 NewSuccessors.push_back(BBCases[i].Dest);
1123 if (SuccHasWeights || PredHasWeights) {
1124 // The default weight is at index 0, so weight for the ith case
1125 // should be at index i+1. Scale the cases from successor by
1126 // PredDefaultWeight (Weights[0]).
1127 Weights.push_back(Weights[0] * SuccWeights[i + 1]);
1128 ValidTotalSuccWeight += SuccWeights[i + 1];
1129 }
1130 }
1131
1132 if (SuccHasWeights || PredHasWeights) {
1133 ValidTotalSuccWeight += SuccWeights[0];
1134 // Scale the cases from predecessor by ValidTotalSuccWeight.
1135 for (unsigned i = 1; i < CasesFromPred; ++i)
1136 Weights[i] *= ValidTotalSuccWeight;
1137 // Scale the default weight by SuccDefaultWeight (SuccWeights[0]).
1138 Weights[0] *= SuccWeights[0];
1139 }
1140 } else {
1141 // If this is not the default destination from PSI, only the edges
1142 // in SI that occur in PSI with a destination of BB will be
1143 // activated.
1144 std::set<ConstantInt *, ConstantIntOrdering> PTIHandled;
1145 std::map<ConstantInt *, uint64_t> WeightsForHandled;
1146 for (unsigned i = 0, e = PredCases.size(); i != e; ++i)
1147 if (PredCases[i].Dest == BB) {
1148 PTIHandled.insert(PredCases[i].Value);
1149
1150 if (PredHasWeights || SuccHasWeights) {
1151 WeightsForHandled[PredCases[i].Value] = Weights[i + 1];
1152 std::swap(Weights[i + 1], Weights.back());
1153 Weights.pop_back();
1154 }
1155
1156 std::swap(PredCases[i], PredCases.back());
1157 PredCases.pop_back();
1158 --i;
1159 --e;
1160 }
1161
1162 // Okay, now we know which constants were sent to BB from the
1163 // predecessor. Figure out where they will all go now.
1164 for (unsigned i = 0, e = BBCases.size(); i != e; ++i)
1165 if (PTIHandled.count(BBCases[i].Value)) {
1166 // If this is one we are capable of getting...
1167 if (PredHasWeights || SuccHasWeights)
1168 Weights.push_back(WeightsForHandled[BBCases[i].Value]);
1169 PredCases.push_back(BBCases[i]);
1170 NewSuccessors.push_back(BBCases[i].Dest);
1171 PTIHandled.erase(
1172 BBCases[i].Value); // This constant is taken care of
1173 }
1174
1175 // If there are any constants vectored to BB that TI doesn't handle,
1176 // they must go to the default destination of TI.
1177 for (ConstantInt *I : PTIHandled) {
1178 if (PredHasWeights || SuccHasWeights)
1179 Weights.push_back(WeightsForHandled[I]);
1180 PredCases.push_back(ValueEqualityComparisonCase(I, BBDefault));
1181 NewSuccessors.push_back(BBDefault);
1182 }
1183 }
1184
1185 // Okay, at this point, we know which new successor Pred will get. Make
1186 // sure we update the number of entries in the PHI nodes for these
1187 // successors.
1188 for (BasicBlock *NewSuccessor : NewSuccessors)
1189 AddPredecessorToBlock(NewSuccessor, Pred, BB);
1190
1191 Builder.SetInsertPoint(PTI);
1192 // Convert pointer to int before we switch.
1193 if (CV->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
1194 CV = Builder.CreatePtrToInt(CV, DL.getIntPtrType(CV->getType()),
1195 "magicptr");
1196 }
1197
1198 // Now that the successors are updated, create the new Switch instruction.
1199 SwitchInst *NewSI =
1200 Builder.CreateSwitch(CV, PredDefault, PredCases.size());
1201 NewSI->setDebugLoc(PTI->getDebugLoc());
1202 for (ValueEqualityComparisonCase &V : PredCases)
1203 NewSI->addCase(V.Value, V.Dest);
1204
1205 if (PredHasWeights || SuccHasWeights) {
1206 // Halve the weights if any of them cannot fit in an uint32_t
1207 FitWeights(Weights);
1208
1209 SmallVector<uint32_t, 8> MDWeights(Weights.begin(), Weights.end());
1210
1211 setBranchWeights(NewSI, MDWeights);
1212 }
1213
1214 EraseTerminatorAndDCECond(PTI);
1215
1216 // Okay, last check. If BB is still a successor of PSI, then we must
1217 // have an infinite loop case. If so, add an infinitely looping block
1218 // to handle the case to preserve the behavior of the code.
1219 BasicBlock *InfLoopBlock = nullptr;
1220 for (unsigned i = 0, e = NewSI->getNumSuccessors(); i != e; ++i)
1221 if (NewSI->getSuccessor(i) == BB) {
1222 if (!InfLoopBlock) {
1223 // Insert it at the end of the function, because it's either code,
1224 // or it won't matter if it's hot. :)
1225 InfLoopBlock = BasicBlock::Create(BB->getContext(), "infloop",
1226 BB->getParent());
1227 BranchInst::Create(InfLoopBlock, InfLoopBlock);
1228 }
1229 NewSI->setSuccessor(i, InfLoopBlock);
1230 }
1231
1232 Changed = true;
1233 }
1234 }
1235 return Changed;
1236}
1237
1238// If we would need to insert a select that uses the value of this invoke
1239// (comments in HoistThenElseCodeToIf explain why we would need to do this), we
1240// can't hoist the invoke, as there is nowhere to put the select in this case.
1241static bool isSafeToHoistInvoke(BasicBlock *BB1, BasicBlock *BB2,
1242 Instruction *I1, Instruction *I2) {
1243 for (BasicBlock *Succ : successors(BB1)) {
1244 for (const PHINode &PN : Succ->phis()) {
1245 Value *BB1V = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(BB1);
1246 Value *BB2V = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(BB2);
1247 if (BB1V != BB2V && (BB1V == I1 || BB2V == I2)) {
1248 return false;
1249 }
1250 }
1251 }
1252 return true;
1253}
1254
1255static bool passingValueIsAlwaysUndefined(Value *V, Instruction *I);
1256
1257/// Given a conditional branch that goes to BB1 and BB2, hoist any common code
1258/// in the two blocks up into the branch block. The caller of this function
1259/// guarantees that BI's block dominates BB1 and BB2.
1260static bool HoistThenElseCodeToIf(BranchInst *BI,
1261 const TargetTransformInfo &TTI) {
1262 // This does very trivial matching, with limited scanning, to find identical
1263 // instructions in the two blocks. In particular, we don't want to get into
1264 // O(M*N) situations here where M and N are the sizes of BB1 and BB2. As
1265 // such, we currently just scan for obviously identical instructions in an
1266 // identical order.
1267 BasicBlock *BB1 = BI->getSuccessor(0); // The true destination.
1268 BasicBlock *BB2 = BI->getSuccessor(1); // The false destination
1269
1270 BasicBlock::iterator BB1_Itr = BB1->begin();
1271 BasicBlock::iterator BB2_Itr = BB2->begin();
1272
1273 Instruction *I1 = &*BB1_Itr++, *I2 = &*BB2_Itr++;
1274 // Skip debug info if it is not identical.
1275 DbgInfoIntrinsic *DBI1 = dyn_cast<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I1);
1276 DbgInfoIntrinsic *DBI2 = dyn_cast<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I2);
1277 if (!DBI1 || !DBI2 || !DBI1->isIdenticalToWhenDefined(DBI2)) {
1278 while (isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I1))
1279 I1 = &*BB1_Itr++;
1280 while (isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I2))
1281 I2 = &*BB2_Itr++;
1282 }
1283 // FIXME: Can we define a safety predicate for CallBr?
1284 if (isa<PHINode>(I1) || !I1->isIdenticalToWhenDefined(I2) ||
1285 (isa<InvokeInst>(I1) && !isSafeToHoistInvoke(BB1, BB2, I1, I2)) ||
1286 isa<CallBrInst>(I1))
1287 return false;
1288
1289 BasicBlock *BIParent = BI->getParent();
1290
1291 bool Changed = false;
1292 do {
1293 // If we are hoisting the terminator instruction, don't move one (making a
1294 // broken BB), instead clone it, and remove BI.
1295 if (I1->isTerminator())
1296 goto HoistTerminator;
1297
1298 // If we're going to hoist a call, make sure that the two instructions we're
1299 // commoning/hoisting are both marked with musttail, or neither of them is
1300 // marked as such. Otherwise, we might end up in a situation where we hoist
1301 // from a block where the terminator is a `ret` to a block where the terminator
1302 // is a `br`, and `musttail` calls expect to be followed by a return.
1303 auto *C1 = dyn_cast<CallInst>(I1);
1304 auto *C2 = dyn_cast<CallInst>(I2);
1305 if (C1 && C2)
1306 if (C1->isMustTailCall() != C2->isMustTailCall())
1307 return Changed;
1308
1309 if (!TTI.isProfitableToHoist(I1) || !TTI.isProfitableToHoist(I2))
1310 return Changed;
1311
1312 if (isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I1) || isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I2)) {
1313 assert (isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I1) && isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I2));
1314 // The debug location is an integral part of a debug info intrinsic
1315 // and can't be separated from it or replaced. Instead of attempting
1316 // to merge locations, simply hoist both copies of the intrinsic.
1317 BIParent->getInstList().splice(BI->getIterator(),
1318 BB1->getInstList(), I1);
1319 BIParent->getInstList().splice(BI->getIterator(),
1320 BB2->getInstList(), I2);
1321 Changed = true;
1322 } else {
1323 // For a normal instruction, we just move one to right before the branch,
1324 // then replace all uses of the other with the first. Finally, we remove
1325 // the now redundant second instruction.
1326 BIParent->getInstList().splice(BI->getIterator(),
1327 BB1->getInstList(), I1);
1328 if (!I2->use_empty())
1329 I2->replaceAllUsesWith(I1);
1330 I1->andIRFlags(I2);
1331 unsigned KnownIDs[] = {LLVMContext::MD_tbaa,
1332 LLVMContext::MD_range,
1333 LLVMContext::MD_fpmath,
1334 LLVMContext::MD_invariant_load,
1335 LLVMContext::MD_nonnull,
1336 LLVMContext::MD_invariant_group,
1337 LLVMContext::MD_align,
1338 LLVMContext::MD_dereferenceable,
1339 LLVMContext::MD_dereferenceable_or_null,
1340 LLVMContext::MD_mem_parallel_loop_access,
1341 LLVMContext::MD_access_group};
1342 combineMetadata(I1, I2, KnownIDs, true);
1343
1344 // I1 and I2 are being combined into a single instruction. Its debug
1345 // location is the merged locations of the original instructions.
1346 I1->applyMergedLocation(I1->getDebugLoc(), I2->getDebugLoc());
1347
1348 I2->eraseFromParent();
1349 Changed = true;
1350 }
1351
1352 I1 = &*BB1_Itr++;
1353 I2 = &*BB2_Itr++;
1354 // Skip debug info if it is not identical.
1355 DbgInfoIntrinsic *DBI1 = dyn_cast<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I1);
1356 DbgInfoIntrinsic *DBI2 = dyn_cast<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I2);
1357 if (!DBI1 || !DBI2 || !DBI1->isIdenticalToWhenDefined(DBI2)) {
1358 while (isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I1))
1359 I1 = &*BB1_Itr++;
1360 while (isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I2))
1361 I2 = &*BB2_Itr++;
1362 }
1363 } while (I1->isIdenticalToWhenDefined(I2));
1364
1365 return true;
1366
1367HoistTerminator:
1368 // It may not be possible to hoist an invoke.
1369 // FIXME: Can we define a safety predicate for CallBr?
1370 if (isa<InvokeInst>(I1) && !isSafeToHoistInvoke(BB1, BB2, I1, I2))
1371 return Changed;
1372
1373 // TODO: callbr hoisting currently disabled pending further study.
1374 if (isa<CallBrInst>(I1))
1375 return Changed;
1376
1377 for (BasicBlock *Succ : successors(BB1)) {
1378 for (PHINode &PN : Succ->phis()) {
1379 Value *BB1V = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(BB1);
1380 Value *BB2V = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(BB2);
1381 if (BB1V == BB2V)
1382 continue;
1383
1384 // Check for passingValueIsAlwaysUndefined here because we would rather
1385 // eliminate undefined control flow then converting it to a select.
1386 if (passingValueIsAlwaysUndefined(BB1V, &PN) ||
1387 passingValueIsAlwaysUndefined(BB2V, &PN))
1388 return Changed;
1389
1390 if (isa<ConstantExpr>(BB1V) && !isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(BB1V))
1391 return Changed;
1392 if (isa<ConstantExpr>(BB2V) && !isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(BB2V))
1393 return Changed;
1394 }
1395 }
1396
1397 // Okay, it is safe to hoist the terminator.
1398 Instruction *NT = I1->clone();
1399 BIParent->getInstList().insert(BI->getIterator(), NT);
1400 if (!NT->getType()->isVoidTy()) {
1401 I1->replaceAllUsesWith(NT);
1402 I2->replaceAllUsesWith(NT);
1403 NT->takeName(I1);
1404 }
1405
1406 // Ensure terminator gets a debug location, even an unknown one, in case
1407 // it involves inlinable calls.
1408 NT->applyMergedLocation(I1->getDebugLoc(), I2->getDebugLoc());
1409
1410 // PHIs created below will adopt NT's merged DebugLoc.
1411 IRBuilder<NoFolder> Builder(NT);
1412
1413 // Hoisting one of the terminators from our successor is a great thing.
1414 // Unfortunately, the successors of the if/else blocks may have PHI nodes in
1415 // them. If they do, all PHI entries for BB1/BB2 must agree for all PHI
1416 // nodes, so we insert select instruction to compute the final result.
1417 std::map<std::pair<Value *, Value *>, SelectInst *> InsertedSelects;
1418 for (BasicBlock *Succ : successors(BB1)) {
1419 for (PHINode &PN : Succ->phis()) {
1420 Value *BB1V = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(BB1);
1421 Value *BB2V = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(BB2);
1422 if (BB1V == BB2V)
1423 continue;
1424
1425 // These values do not agree. Insert a select instruction before NT
1426 // that determines the right value.
1427 SelectInst *&SI = InsertedSelects[std::make_pair(BB1V, BB2V)];
1428 if (!SI)
1429 SI = cast<SelectInst>(
1430 Builder.CreateSelect(BI->getCondition(), BB1V, BB2V,
1431 BB1V->getName() + "." + BB2V->getName(), BI));
1432
1433 // Make the PHI node use the select for all incoming values for BB1/BB2
1434 for (unsigned i = 0, e = PN.getNumIncomingValues(); i != e; ++i)
1435 if (PN.getIncomingBlock(i) == BB1 || PN.getIncomingBlock(i) == BB2)
1436 PN.setIncomingValue(i, SI);
1437 }
1438 }
1439
1440 // Update any PHI nodes in our new successors.
1441 for (BasicBlock *Succ : successors(BB1))
1442 AddPredecessorToBlock(Succ, BIParent, BB1);
1443
1444 EraseTerminatorAndDCECond(BI);
1445 return true;
1446}
1447
1448// All instructions in Insts belong to different blocks that all unconditionally
1449// branch to a common successor. Analyze each instruction and return true if it
1450// would be possible to sink them into their successor, creating one common
1451// instruction instead. For every value that would be required to be provided by
1452// PHI node (because an operand varies in each input block), add to PHIOperands.
1453static bool canSinkInstructions(
1454 ArrayRef<Instruction *> Insts,
1455 DenseMap<Instruction *, SmallVector<Value *, 4>> &PHIOperands) {
1456 // Prune out obviously bad instructions to move. Any non-store instruction
1457 // must have exactly one use, and we check later that use is by a single,
1458 // common PHI instruction in the successor.
1459 for (auto *I : Insts) {
1460 // These instructions may change or break semantics if moved.
1461 if (isa<PHINode>(I) || I->isEHPad() || isa<AllocaInst>(I) ||
1462 I->getType()->isTokenTy())
1463 return false;
1464
1465 // Conservatively return false if I is an inline-asm instruction. Sinking
1466 // and merging inline-asm instructions can potentially create arguments
1467 // that cannot satisfy the inline-asm constraints.
1468 if (const auto *C = dyn_cast<CallBase>(I))
1469 if (C->isInlineAsm())
1470 return false;
1471
1472 // Everything must have only one use too, apart from stores which
1473 // have no uses.
1474 if (!isa<StoreInst>(I) && !I->hasOneUse())
1475 return false;
1476 }
1477
1478 const Instruction *I0 = Insts.front();
1479 for (auto *I : Insts)
1480 if (!I->isSameOperationAs(I0))
1481 return false;
1482
1483 // All instructions in Insts are known to be the same opcode. If they aren't
1484 // stores, check the only user of each is a PHI or in the same block as the
1485 // instruction, because if a user is in the same block as an instruction
1486 // we're contemplating sinking, it must already be determined to be sinkable.
1487 if (!isa<StoreInst>(I0)) {
1488 auto *PNUse = dyn_cast<PHINode>(*I0->user_begin());
1489 auto *Succ = I0->getParent()->getTerminator()->getSuccessor(0);
1490 if (!all_of(Insts, [&PNUse,&Succ](const Instruction *I) -> bool {
1491 auto *U = cast<Instruction>(*I->user_begin());
1492 return (PNUse &&
1493 PNUse->getParent() == Succ &&
1494 PNUse->getIncomingValueForBlock(I->getParent()) == I) ||
1495 U->getParent() == I->getParent();
1496 }))
1497 return false;
1498 }
1499
1500 // Because SROA can't handle speculating stores of selects, try not
1501 // to sink loads or stores of allocas when we'd have to create a PHI for
1502 // the address operand. Also, because it is likely that loads or stores
1503 // of allocas will disappear when Mem2Reg/SROA is run, don't sink them.
1504 // This can cause code churn which can have unintended consequences down
1505 // the line - see https://llvm.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=30244.
1506 // FIXME: This is a workaround for a deficiency in SROA - see
1507 // https://llvm.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=30188
1508 if (isa<StoreInst>(I0) && any_of(Insts, [](const Instruction *I) {
1509 return isa<AllocaInst>(I->getOperand(1));
1510 }))
1511 return false;
1512 if (isa<LoadInst>(I0) && any_of(Insts, [](const Instruction *I) {
1513 return isa<AllocaInst>(I->getOperand(0));
1514 }))
1515 return false;
1516
1517 for (unsigned OI = 0, OE = I0->getNumOperands(); OI != OE; ++OI) {
1518 if (I0->getOperand(OI)->getType()->isTokenTy())
1519 // Don't touch any operand of token type.
1520 return false;
1521
1522 auto SameAsI0 = [&I0, OI](const Instruction *I) {
1523 assert(I->getNumOperands() == I0->getNumOperands());
1524 return I->getOperand(OI) == I0->getOperand(OI);
1525 };
1526 if (!all_of(Insts, SameAsI0)) {
1527 if (!canReplaceOperandWithVariable(I0, OI))
1528 // We can't create a PHI from this GEP.
1529 return false;
1530 // Don't create indirect calls! The called value is the final operand.
1531 if (isa<CallBase>(I0) && OI == OE - 1) {
1532 // FIXME: if the call was *already* indirect, we should do this.
1533 return false;
1534 }
1535 for (auto *I : Insts)
1536 PHIOperands[I].push_back(I->getOperand(OI));
1537 }
1538 }
1539 return true;
1540}
1541
1542// Assuming canSinkLastInstruction(Blocks) has returned true, sink the last
1543// instruction of every block in Blocks to their common successor, commoning
1544// into one instruction.
1545static bool sinkLastInstruction(ArrayRef<BasicBlock*> Blocks) {
1546 auto *BBEnd = Blocks[0]->getTerminator()->getSuccessor(0);
1547
1548 // canSinkLastInstruction returning true guarantees that every block has at
1549 // least one non-terminator instruction.
1550 SmallVector<Instruction*,4> Insts;
1551 for (auto *BB : Blocks) {
1552 Instruction *I = BB->getTerminator();
1553 do {
1554 I = I->getPrevNode();
1555 } while (isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I) && I != &BB->front());
1556 if (!isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I))
1557 Insts.push_back(I);
1558 }
1559
1560 // The only checking we need to do now is that all users of all instructions
1561 // are the same PHI node. canSinkLastInstruction should have checked this but
1562 // it is slightly over-aggressive - it gets confused by commutative instructions
1563 // so double-check it here.
1564 Instruction *I0 = Insts.front();
1565 if (!isa<StoreInst>(I0)) {
1566 auto *PNUse = dyn_cast<PHINode>(*I0->user_begin());
1567 if (!all_of(Insts, [&PNUse](const Instruction *I) -> bool {
1568 auto *U = cast<Instruction>(*I->user_begin());
1569 return U == PNUse;
1570 }))
1571 return false;
1572 }
1573
1574 // We don't need to do any more checking here; canSinkLastInstruction should
1575 // have done it all for us.
1576 SmallVector<Value*, 4> NewOperands;
1577 for (unsigned O = 0, E = I0->getNumOperands(); O != E; ++O) {
1578 // This check is different to that in canSinkLastInstruction. There, we
1579 // cared about the global view once simplifycfg (and instcombine) have
1580 // completed - it takes into account PHIs that become trivially
1581 // simplifiable. However here we need a more local view; if an operand
1582 // differs we create a PHI and rely on instcombine to clean up the very
1583 // small mess we may make.
1584 bool NeedPHI = any_of(Insts, [&I0, O](const Instruction *I) {
1585 return I->getOperand(O) != I0->getOperand(O);
1586 });
1587 if (!NeedPHI) {
1588 NewOperands.push_back(I0->getOperand(O));
1589 continue;
1590 }
1591
1592 // Create a new PHI in the successor block and populate it.
1593 auto *Op = I0->getOperand(O);
1594 assert(!Op->getType()->isTokenTy() && "Can't PHI tokens!");
1595 auto *PN = PHINode::Create(Op->getType(), Insts.size(),
1596 Op->getName() + ".sink", &BBEnd->front());
1597 for (auto *I : Insts)
1598 PN->addIncoming(I->getOperand(O), I->getParent());
1599 NewOperands.push_back(PN);
1600 }
1601
1602 // Arbitrarily use I0 as the new "common" instruction; remap its operands
1603 // and move it to the start of the successor block.
1604 for (unsigned O = 0, E = I0->getNumOperands(); O != E; ++O)
1605 I0->getOperandUse(O).set(NewOperands[O]);
1606 I0->moveBefore(&*BBEnd->getFirstInsertionPt());
1607
1608 // Update metadata and IR flags, and merge debug locations.
1609 for (auto *I : Insts)
1610 if (I != I0) {
1611 // The debug location for the "common" instruction is the merged locations
1612 // of all the commoned instructions. We start with the original location
1613 // of the "common" instruction and iteratively merge each location in the
1614 // loop below.
1615 // This is an N-way merge, which will be inefficient if I0 is a CallInst.
1616 // However, as N-way merge for CallInst is rare, so we use simplified API
1617 // instead of using complex API for N-way merge.
1618 I0->applyMergedLocation(I0->getDebugLoc(), I->getDebugLoc());
1619 combineMetadataForCSE(I0, I, true);
1620 I0->andIRFlags(I);
1621 }
1622
1623 if (!isa<StoreInst>(I0)) {
1624 // canSinkLastInstruction checked that all instructions were used by
1625 // one and only one PHI node. Find that now, RAUW it to our common
1626 // instruction and nuke it.
1627 assert(I0->hasOneUse());
1628 auto *PN = cast<PHINode>(*I0->user_begin());
1629 PN->replaceAllUsesWith(I0);
1630 PN->eraseFromParent();
1631 }
1632
1633 // Finally nuke all instructions apart from the common instruction.
1634 for (auto *I : Insts)
1635 if (I != I0)
1636 I->eraseFromParent();
1637
1638 return true;
1639}

1641namespace {

1643 // LockstepReverseIterator - Iterates through instructions
1644 // in a set of blocks in reverse order from the first non-terminator.
1645 // For example (assume all blocks have size n):
1646 // LockstepReverseIterator I([B1, B2, B3]);
1647 // *I-- = [B1[n], B2[n], B3[n]];
1648 // *I-- = [B1[n-1], B2[n-1], B3[n-1]];
1649 // *I-- = [B1[n-2], B2[n-2], B3[n-2]];
1650 // ...
1651 class LockstepReverseIterator {
1652 ArrayRef<BasicBlock*> Blocks;
1653 SmallVector<Instruction*,4> Insts;
1654 bool Fail;
1655
1656 public:
1657 LockstepReverseIterator(ArrayRef<BasicBlock*> Blocks) : Blocks(Blocks) {
1658 reset();
1659 }
1660
1661 void reset() {
1662 Fail = false;
1663 Insts.clear();
1664 for (auto *BB : Blocks) {
1665 Instruction *Inst = BB->getTerminator();
1666 for (Inst = Inst->getPrevNode(); Inst && isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(Inst);)
1667 Inst = Inst->getPrevNode();
1668 if (!Inst) {
1669 // Block wasn't big enough.
1670 Fail = true;
1671 return;
1672 }
1673 Insts.push_back(Inst);
1674 }
1675 }
1676
1677 bool isValid() const {
1678 return !Fail;
1679 }
1680
1681 void operator--() {
1682 if (Fail)
1683 return;
1684 for (auto *&Inst : Insts) {
1685 for (Inst = Inst->getPrevNode(); Inst && isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(Inst);)
1686 Inst = Inst->getPrevNode();
1687 // Already at beginning of block.
1688 if (!Inst) {
1689 Fail = true;
1690 return;
1691 }
1692 }
1693 }
1694
1695 ArrayRef<Instruction*> operator * () const {
1696 return Insts;
1697 }
1698 };
1699
1700} // end anonymous namespace

1702/// Check whether BB's predecessors end with unconditional branches. If it is
1703/// true, sink any common code from the predecessors to BB.
1704/// We also allow one predecessor to end with conditional branch (but no more
1705/// than one).
1706static bool SinkCommonCodeFromPredecessors(BasicBlock *BB) {
1707 // We support two situations:
1708 // (1) all incoming arcs are unconditional
1709 // (2) one incoming arc is conditional
1710 //
1711 // (2) is very common in switch defaults and
1712 // else-if patterns;
1713 //
1714 // if (a) f(1);
1715 // else if (b) f(2);
1716 //
1717 // produces:
1718 //
1719 // [if]
1720 // / \
1721 // [f(1)] [if]
1722 // | | \
1723 // | | |
1724 // | [f(2)]|
1725 // \ | /
1726 // [ end ]
1727 //
1728 // [end] has two unconditional predecessor arcs and one conditional. The
1729 // conditional refers to the implicit empty 'else' arc. This conditional
1730 // arc can also be caused by an empty default block in a switch.
1731 //
1732 // In this case, we attempt to sink code from all *unconditional* arcs.
1733 // If we can sink instructions from these arcs (determined during the scan
1734 // phase below) we insert a common successor for all unconditional arcs and
1735 // connect that to [end], to enable sinking:
1736 //
1737 // [if]
1738 // / \
1739 // [x(1)] [if]
1740 // | | \
1741 // | | \
1742 // | [x(2)] |
1743 // \ / |
1744 // [sink.split] |
1745 // \ /
1746 // [ end ]
1747 //
1748 SmallVector<BasicBlock*,4> UnconditionalPreds;
1749 Instruction *Cond = nullptr;
1750 for (auto *B : predecessors(BB)) {
1751 auto *T = B->getTerminator();
1752 if (isa<BranchInst>(T) && cast<BranchInst>(T)->isUnconditional())
1753 UnconditionalPreds.push_back(B);
1754 else if ((isa<BranchInst>(T) || isa<SwitchInst>(T)) && !Cond)
1755 Cond = T;
1756 else
1757 return false;
1758 }
1759 if (UnconditionalPreds.size() < 2)
1760 return false;
1761
1762 bool Changed = false;
1763 // We take a two-step approach to tail sinking. First we scan from the end of
1764 // each block upwards in lockstep. If the n'th instruction from the end of each
1765 // block can be sunk, those instructions are added to ValuesToSink and we
1766 // carry on. If we can sink an instruction but need to PHI-merge some operands
1767 // (because they're not identical in each instruction) we add these to
1768 // PHIOperands.
1769 unsigned ScanIdx = 0;
1770 SmallPtrSet<Value*,4> InstructionsToSink;
1771 DenseMap<Instruction*, SmallVector<Value*,4>> PHIOperands;
1772 LockstepReverseIterator LRI(UnconditionalPreds);
1773 while (LRI.isValid() &&
1774 canSinkInstructions(*LRI, PHIOperands)) {
1775 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SINK: instruction can be sunk: " << *(*LRI)[0]
1776 << "\n");
1777 InstructionsToSink.insert((*LRI).begin(), (*LRI).end());
1778 ++ScanIdx;
1779 --LRI;
1780 }
1781
1782 auto ProfitableToSinkInstruction = [&](LockstepReverseIterator &LRI) {
1783 unsigned NumPHIdValues = 0;
1784 for (auto *I : *LRI)
1785 for (auto *V : PHIOperands[I])
1786 if (InstructionsToSink.count(V) == 0)
1787 ++NumPHIdValues;
1788 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SINK: #phid values: " << NumPHIdValues << "\n");
1789 unsigned NumPHIInsts = NumPHIdValues / UnconditionalPreds.size();
1790 if ((NumPHIdValues % UnconditionalPreds.size()) != 0)
1791 NumPHIInsts++;
1792
1793 return NumPHIInsts <= 1;
1794 };
1795
1796 if (ScanIdx > 0 && Cond) {
1797 // Check if we would actually sink anything first! This mutates the CFG and
1798 // adds an extra block. The goal in doing this is to allow instructions that
1799 // couldn't be sunk before to be sunk - obviously, speculatable instructions
1800 // (such as trunc, add) can be sunk and predicated already. So we check that
1801 // we're going to sink at least one non-speculatable instruction.
1802 LRI.reset();
1803 unsigned Idx = 0;
1804 bool Profitable = false;
1805 while (ProfitableToSinkInstruction(LRI) && Idx < ScanIdx) {
1806 if (!isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute((*LRI)[0])) {
1807 Profitable = true;
1808 break;
1809 }
1810 --LRI;
1811 ++Idx;
1812 }
1813 if (!Profitable)
1814 return false;
1815
1816 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SINK: Splitting edge\n");
1817 // We have a conditional edge and we're going to sink some instructions.
1818 // Insert a new block postdominating all blocks we're going to sink from.
1819 if (!SplitBlockPredecessors(BB, UnconditionalPreds, ".sink.split"))
1820 // Edges couldn't be split.
1821 return false;
1822 Changed = true;
1823 }
1824
1825 // Now that we've analyzed all potential sinking candidates, perform the
1826 // actual sink. We iteratively sink the last non-terminator of the source
1827 // blocks into their common successor unless doing so would require too
1828 // many PHI instructions to be generated (currently only one PHI is allowed
1829 // per sunk instruction).
1830 //
1831 // We can use InstructionsToSink to discount values needing PHI-merging that will
1832 // actually be sunk in a later iteration. This allows us to be more
1833 // aggressive in what we sink. This does allow a false positive where we
1834 // sink presuming a later value will also be sunk, but stop half way through
1835 // and never actually sink it which means we produce more PHIs than intended.
1836 // This is unlikely in practice though.
1837 for (unsigned SinkIdx = 0; SinkIdx != ScanIdx; ++SinkIdx) {
1838 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SINK: Sink: "
1839 << *UnconditionalPreds[0]->getTerminator()->getPrevNode()
1840 << "\n");
1841
1842 // Because we've sunk every instruction in turn, the current instruction to
1843 // sink is always at index 0.
1844 LRI.reset();
1845 if (!ProfitableToSinkInstruction(LRI)) {
1846 // Too many PHIs would be created.
1847 LLVM_DEBUG(
1848 dbgs() << "SINK: stopping here, too many PHIs would be created!\n");
1849 break;
1850 }
1851
1852 if (!sinkLastInstruction(UnconditionalPreds))
1853 return Changed;
1854 NumSinkCommons++;
1855 Changed = true;
1856 }
1857 return Changed;
1858}
1859
1860/// Determine if we can hoist sink a sole store instruction out of a
1861/// conditional block.
1862///
1863/// We are looking for code like the following:
1864/// BrBB:
1865/// store i32 %add, i32* %arrayidx2
1866/// ... // No other stores or function calls (we could be calling a memory
1867/// ... // function).
1868/// %cmp = icmp ult %x, %y
1869/// br i1 %cmp, label %EndBB, label %ThenBB
1870/// ThenBB:
1871/// store i32 %add5, i32* %arrayidx2
1872/// br label EndBB
1873/// EndBB:
1874/// ...
1875/// We are going to transform this into:
1876/// BrBB:
1877/// store i32 %add, i32* %arrayidx2
1878/// ... //
1879/// %cmp = icmp ult %x, %y
1880/// %add.add5 = select i1 %cmp, i32 %add, %add5
1881/// store i32 %add.add5, i32* %arrayidx2
1882/// ...
1883///
1884/// \return The pointer to the value of the previous store if the store can be
1885/// hoisted into the predecessor block. 0 otherwise.
1886static Value *isSafeToSpeculateStore(Instruction *I, BasicBlock *BrBB,
1887 BasicBlock *StoreBB, BasicBlock *EndBB) {
1888 StoreInst *StoreToHoist = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(I);
1889 if (!StoreToHoist)
1890 return nullptr;
1891
1892 // Volatile or atomic.
1893 if (!StoreToHoist->isSimple())
1894 return nullptr;
1895
1896 Value *StorePtr = StoreToHoist->getPointerOperand();
1897
1898 // Look for a store to the same pointer in BrBB.
1899 unsigned MaxNumInstToLookAt = 9;
1900 for (Instruction &CurI : reverse(BrBB->instructionsWithoutDebug())) {
1901 if (!MaxNumInstToLookAt)
1902 break;
1903 --MaxNumInstToLookAt;
1904
1905 // Could be calling an instruction that affects memory like free().
1906 if (CurI.mayHaveSideEffects() && !isa<StoreInst>(CurI))
1907 return nullptr;
1908
1909 if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(&CurI)) {
1910 // Found the previous store make sure it stores to the same location.
1911 if (SI->getPointerOperand() == StorePtr)
1912 // Found the previous store, return its value operand.
1913 return SI->getValueOperand();
1914 return nullptr; // Unknown store.
1915 }
1916 }
1917
1918 return nullptr;
1919}
1920
1921/// Speculate a conditional basic block flattening the CFG.
1922///
1923/// Note that this is a very risky transform currently. Speculating
1924/// instructions like this is most often not desirable. Instead, there is an MI
1925/// pass which can do it with full awareness of the resource constraints.
1926/// However, some cases are "obvious" and we should do directly. An example of
1927/// this is speculating a single, reasonably cheap instruction.
1928///
1929/// There is only one distinct advantage to flattening the CFG at the IR level:
1930/// it makes very common but simplistic optimizations such as are common in
1931/// instcombine and the DAG combiner more powerful by removing CFG edges and
1932/// modeling their effects with easier to reason about SSA value graphs.
1933///
1934///
1935/// An illustration of this transform is turning this IR:
1936/// \code
1937/// BB:
1938/// %cmp = icmp ult %x, %y
1939/// br i1 %cmp, label %EndBB, label %ThenBB
1940/// ThenBB:
1941/// %sub = sub %x, %y
1942/// br label BB2
1943/// EndBB:
1944/// %phi = phi [ %sub, %ThenBB ], [ 0, %EndBB ]
1945/// ...
1946/// \endcode
1947///
1948/// Into this IR:
1949/// \code
1950/// BB:
1951/// %cmp = icmp ult %x, %y
1952/// %sub = sub %x, %y
1953/// %cond = select i1 %cmp, 0, %sub
1954/// ...
1955/// \endcode
1956///
1957/// \returns true if the conditional block is removed.
1958static bool SpeculativelyExecuteBB(BranchInst *BI, BasicBlock *ThenBB,
1959 const TargetTransformInfo &TTI) {
1960 // Be conservative for now. FP select instruction can often be expensive.
1961 Value *BrCond = BI->getCondition();
1962 if (isa<FCmpInst>(BrCond))
1963 return false;
1964
1965 BasicBlock *BB = BI->getParent();
1966 BasicBlock *EndBB = ThenBB->getTerminator()->getSuccessor(0);
1967
1968 // If ThenBB is actually on the false edge of the conditional branch, remember
1969 // to swap the select operands later.
1970 bool Invert = false;
1971 if (ThenBB != BI->getSuccessor(0)) {
1972 assert(ThenBB == BI->getSuccessor(1) && "No edge from 'if' block?");
1973 Invert = true;
1974 }
1975 assert(EndBB == BI->getSuccessor(!Invert) && "No edge from to end block");
1976
1977 // Keep a count of how many times instructions are used within ThenBB when
1978 // they are candidates for sinking into ThenBB. Specifically:
1979 // - They are defined in BB, and
1980 // - They have no side effects, and
1981 // - All of their uses are in ThenBB.
1982 SmallDenseMap<Instruction *, unsigned, 4> SinkCandidateUseCounts;
1983
1984 SmallVector<Instruction *, 4> SpeculatedDbgIntrinsics;
1985
1986 unsigned SpeculationCost = 0;
1987 Value *SpeculatedStoreValue = nullptr;
1988 StoreInst *SpeculatedStore = nullptr;
1989 for (BasicBlock::iterator BBI = ThenBB->begin(),
1990 BBE = std::prev(ThenBB->end());
1991 BBI != BBE; ++BBI) {
1992 Instruction *I = &*BBI;
1993 // Skip debug info.
1994 if (isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(I)) {
1995 SpeculatedDbgIntrinsics.push_back(I);
1996 continue;
1997 }
1998
1999 // Only speculatively execute a single instruction (not counting the
2000 // terminator) for now.
2001 ++SpeculationCost;
2002 if (SpeculationCost > 1)
2003 return false;
2004
2005 // Don't hoist the instruction if it's unsafe or expensive.
2006 if (!isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(I) &&
2007 !(HoistCondStores && (SpeculatedStoreValue = isSafeToSpeculateStore(
2008 I, BB, ThenBB, EndBB))))
2009 return false;
2010 if (!SpeculatedStoreValue &&
2011 ComputeSpeculationCost(I, TTI) >
2012 PHINodeFoldingThreshold * TargetTransformInfo::TCC_Basic)
2013 return false;
2014
2015 // Store the store speculation candidate.
2016 if (SpeculatedStoreValue)
2017 SpeculatedStore = cast<StoreInst>(I);
2018
2019 // Do not hoist the instruction if any of its operands are defined but not
2020 // used in BB. The transformation will prevent the operand from
2021 // being sunk into the use block.
2022 for (User::op_iterator i = I->op_begin(), e = I->op_end(); i != e; ++i) {
2023 Instruction *OpI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(*i);
2024 if (!OpI || OpI->getParent() != BB || OpI->mayHaveSideEffects())
2025 continue; // Not a candidate for sinking.
2026
2027 ++SinkCandidateUseCounts[OpI];
2028 }
2029 }
2030
2031 // Consider any sink candidates which are only used in ThenBB as costs for
2032 // speculation. Note, while we iterate over a DenseMap here, we are summing
2033 // and so iteration order isn't significant.
2034 for (SmallDenseMap<Instruction *, unsigned, 4>::iterator
2035 I = SinkCandidateUseCounts.begin(),
2036 E = SinkCandidateUseCounts.end();
2037 I != E; ++I)
2038 if (I->first->hasNUses(I->second)) {
2039 ++SpeculationCost;
2040 if (SpeculationCost > 1)
2041 return false;
2042 }
2043
2044 // Check that the PHI nodes can be converted to selects.
2045 bool HaveRewritablePHIs = false;
2046 for (PHINode &PN : EndBB->phis()) {
2047 Value *OrigV = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(BB);
2048 Value *ThenV = PN.getIncomingValueForBlock(ThenBB);
2049
2050 // FIXME: Try to remove some of the duplication with HoistThenElseCodeToIf.
2051 // Skip PHIs which are trivial.
2052 if (ThenV == OrigV)
2053 continue;
2054
2055 // Don't convert to selects if we could remove undefined behavior instead.
2056 if (passingValueIsAlwaysUndefined(OrigV, &PN) ||
2057 passingValueIsAlwaysUndefined(ThenV, &PN))
2058 return false;
2059
2060 HaveRewritablePHIs = true;
2061 ConstantExpr *OrigCE = dyn_cast<ConstantExpr>(OrigV);
2062 ConstantExpr *ThenCE = dyn_cast<ConstantExpr>(ThenV);
2063 if (!OrigCE && !ThenCE)
2064 continue; // Known safe and cheap.
2065
2066 if ((ThenCE && !isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(ThenCE)) ||
2067 (OrigCE && !isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(OrigCE)))
2068 return false;
2069 unsigned OrigCost = OrigCE ? ComputeSpeculationCost(OrigCE, TTI) : 0;
2070 unsigned ThenCost = ThenCE ? ComputeSpeculationCost(ThenCE, TTI) : 0;
2071 unsigned MaxCost =
2072 2 * PHINodeFoldingThreshold * TargetTransformInfo::TCC_Basic;
2073 if (OrigCost + ThenCost > MaxCost)
2074 return false;
2075
2076 // Account for the cost of an unfolded ConstantExpr which could end up
2077 // getting expanded into Instructions.
2078 // FIXME: This doesn't account for how many operations are combined in the
2079 // constant expression.
2080 ++SpeculationCost;
2081 if (SpeculationCost > 1)
2082 return false;
2083 }
2084
2085 // If there are no PHIs to process, bail early. This helps ensure idempotence
2086 // as well.
2087 if (!HaveRewritablePHIs && !(HoistCondStores && SpeculatedStoreValue))
2088 return false;
2089
2090 // If we get here, we can hoist the instruction and if-convert.
2091 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SPECULATIVELY EXECUTING BB" << *ThenBB << "\n";);
2092
2093 // Insert a select of the value of the speculated store.
2094 if (SpeculatedStoreValue) {
2095 IRBuilder<NoFolder> Builder(BI);
2096 Value *TrueV = SpeculatedStore->getValueOperand();
2097 Value *FalseV = SpeculatedStoreValue;
2098 if (Invert)
2099 std::swap(TrueV, FalseV);
2100 Value *S = Builder.CreateSelect(
2101 BrCond, TrueV, FalseV, "spec.store.select", BI);
2102 SpeculatedStore->setOperand(0, S);
2103 SpeculatedStore->applyMergedLocation(BI->getDebugLoc(),
2104 SpeculatedStore->getDebugLoc());
2105 }
2106
2107 // Metadata can be dependent on the condition we are hoisting above.
2108 // Conservatively strip all metadata on the instruction.
2109 for (auto &I : *ThenBB)
2110 I.dropUnknownNonDebugMetadata();
2111
2112 // Hoist the instructions.
2113 BB->getInstList().splice(BI->getIterator(), ThenBB->getInstList(),
2114 ThenBB->begin(), std::prev(ThenBB->end()));
2115
2116 // Insert selects and rewrite the PHI operands.
2117 IRBuilder<NoFolder> Builder(BI);
2118 for (PHINode &PN : EndBB->phis()) {
2119 unsigned OrigI = PN.getBasicBlockIndex(BB);
2120 unsigned ThenI = PN.getBasicBlockIndex(ThenBB);
2121 Value *OrigV = PN.getIncomingValue(OrigI);
2122 Value *ThenV = PN.getIncomingValue(ThenI);
2123
2124 // Skip PHIs which are trivial.
2125 if (OrigV == ThenV)
2126 continue;
2127
2128 // Create a select whose true value is the speculatively executed value and
2129 // false value is the preexisting value. Swap them if the branch
2130 // destinations were inverted.
2131 Value *TrueV = ThenV, *FalseV = OrigV;
2132 if (Invert)
2133 std::swap(TrueV, FalseV);
2134 Value *V = Builder.CreateSelect(
2135 BrCond, TrueV, FalseV, "spec.select", BI);
2136 PN.setIncomingValue(OrigI, V);
2137 PN.setIncomingValue(ThenI, V);
2138 }
2139
2140 // Remove speculated dbg intrinsics.
2141 // FIXME: Is it possible to do this in a more elegant way? Moving/merging the
2142 // dbg value for the different flows and inserting it after the select.
2143 for (Instruction *I : SpeculatedDbgIntrinsics)
2144 I->eraseFromParent();
2145
2146 ++NumSpeculations;
2147 return true;
2148}

2150/// Return true if we can thread a branch across this block.
2151static bool BlockIsSimpleEnoughToThreadThrough(BasicBlock *BB) {
2152 unsigned Size = 0;
2153
2154 for (Instruction &I : BB->instructionsWithoutDebug()) {
2155 if (Size > 10)
2156 return false; // Don't clone large BB's.
2157 ++Size;
2158
2159 // We can only support instructions that do not define values that are
2160 // live outside of the current basic block.
2161 for (User *U : I.users()) {
2162 Instruction *UI = cast<Instruction>(U);
2163 if (UI->getParent() != BB || isa<PHINode>(UI))
2164 return false;
2165 }
2166
2167 // Looks ok, continue checking.
2168 }
2169
2170 return true;
2171}
